<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,150,429]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,150,176]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species was previously recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[841,986,150,176]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dabbour, A. I." box="[1027,1212,150,176]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="81 - 83" refId="ref31087" refString="Dabbour, A. I. (1979 a) Short note on dipterous flies in western and central regions of Saudi Arabia. Journal of Agriculture Research, Riyadh University, 4, 81 - 83." type="journal article" year="1979">Dabbour (1979a</bibRefCitation>
; b); 
<bibRefCitation author="Abu-Zoherah, R. &amp; Al-Taher, K. &amp; Tilkian, S." pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref29552" refString="Abu-Zoherah, R., Al-Taher, K. &amp; Tilkian, S. (1993) List of Insects Recorded from Saudi Arabia. Ministry of Agriculture and Water, National Agriculture and Water Research Centre, Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, Riyadh, 394 pp." type="book" year="1993">
Abu-Zoherah 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al</emphasis>
. (1993)
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Al-Misned, F. A. M." box="[275,481,186,212]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="119 - 123" refId="ref29764" refString="Al-Misned, F. A. M. (2003) Ophyra capensis (Wiedemann, 1818) (Diptera: Muscidae) a muscid species new for Saudi Arabia. Pakistan Journal of Zoology, 35 (2), 119 - 123." type="journal article" year="2003">Al-Misned (2003)</bibRefCitation>
. It was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[741,887,186,212]" name="South Africa" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">South Africa</collectingCountry>
. In the Middle East it is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[1303,1373,187,213]" name="Egypt" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Egypt</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1384,1432,187,213]" name="Iran" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Iran</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,216,222,248]" name="Israel" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Israel</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[227,298,222,248]" name="Oman" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Oman</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[310,372,222,248]" name="Syria" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Syria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[382,462,222,248]" name="Turkey" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Turkey</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[516,594,223,249]" name="Yemen" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Yemen</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[608,727,222,248]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref34968" refString="Pont, A. C. (1986) Families Fannidae, Muscidae. In: Soos, A. &amp; Papp. L. (Eds.), Catalogue of Palaearctic Diptera, Scathophagidae-Hypodermatidae. Vol. 11. Akademiai Kiado, Budapest, pp. 57 - 215." type="book" year="1986">Pont 1986</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[739,857,222,249]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref35020" refString="Pont, A. C. (1991) A review of the Fanniidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of the Arabian Peninsula. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 12, 312 - 265." type="book" year="1991">Pont 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Deeming, J. C." box="[868,1039,222,248]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref31673" refString="Deeming, J. C. (2008) Order Diptera, family Muscidae. In: van Harten, A. (Ed.), Arthropod Fauna of the United Arab Emirates. Vol. 1. Dar Al-Ummah Printing, Publishing, Distribution &amp; Advertising, Abu Dhabi, pp. 714 - 723." type="book" year="2008">Deeming 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,150,429]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,431,258,284]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Biological remarks.</emphasis>
Larvae (third instar) develop as predators of other soft-bodied insect larvae mostly in dung and carrion (
<bibRefCitation author="Skidmore, P." box="[295,473,294,321]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref36277" refString="Skidmore, P. (1985) The Biology of the Muscidae of the World. Series Entomologica 29. Dr. W. Junk Publishers, Dordrecht, 550 pp." type="book" year="1985">Skidmore 1985</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Deeming, J. C." box="[486,657,294,320]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref31673" refString="Deeming, J. C. (2008) Order Diptera, family Muscidae. In: van Harten, A. (Ed.), Arthropod Fauna of the United Arab Emirates. Vol. 1. Dar Al-Ummah Printing, Publishing, Distribution &amp; Advertising, Abu Dhabi, pp. 714 - 723." type="book" year="2008">Deeming 2008</bibRefCitation>
). This species has also been reared from bird and mammal nests and from fungi (
<bibRefCitation author="Skidmore, P." box="[289,468,330,357]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref36277" refString="Skidmore, P. (1985) The Biology of the Muscidae of the World. Series Entomologica 29. Dr. W. Junk Publishers, Dordrecht, 550 pp." type="book" year="1985">Skidmore 1985</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Couri, M. S. &amp; Cunha, A. M. &amp; De Souza, S. M. F. M. &amp; Laeta, M." box="[489,701,330,357]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="87 - 91" refId="ref30881" refString="Couri, M. S., Cunha, A. M., De Souza, S. M. F. M. &amp; Laeta, M. (2009) Ophyra capensis (Wiedemann, 1818) (Diptera: Muscidae) found inside the oesophagous of a mummy in Lisbon. Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 49 (6), 87 - 91. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0031 - 10492009000600001" type="journal article" year="2009">
Couri 
<emphasis box="[561,611,330,356]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al</emphasis>
. (2009)
</bibRefCitation>
found within the oesophagous of a mummified human corpse at “ 
<collectingRegion box="[161,244,366,392]" country="Portugal" name="Lisboa" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Lisbon</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[255,353,366,392]" name="Portugal" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Portugal</collectingCountry>
” dating from the 19 
<superScript attach="left" box="[574,587,366,380]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">th</superScript>
century a number of larvae, pupae and adult remains of 
<taxonomicName box="[1213,1332,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Hydrotaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capensi">
<emphasis box="[1213,1332,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">H. capensi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s and cite further reports.
</paragraph>
